@_arsenick_ yeah and you just took the words right out of my mouth. luxury doesn't have to be flashy, but companies still make flashy products because there's a demand, by the nouveau riche as the primary market. I dont know if you are still struggling to understand the distinction im trying to make by specifically citing the term 'primary market'. I was also commenting on the common attitude of need for attention among the primary market, not how subversive of a old money kid you can be by taking fashion insp from the nouveau riche crowd. you said that you like the LV monogram, so I assumed you were referring to the singular logo instead of collectivised patterns. furthermore, what's wrong with flexing something thats not worth at least 100k? are people supposed to not take pride in their ownership of a certain object just because of the monetary value of that object? should people not be proud of what they own because they weren't born with a trust fund supporting their consumption habits? your family has the option of denying a Royce, but some families save tooth and nail to even afford basic necessities, should they not feel pride when they can take care of their family despite their lack of financial endowment at birth?

@_arsenick_ if you genuinely like the logo and want a bag full of logos, go loco. design unlike art, is more business-oriented so design will always take into budget constraints and consumer attitude. in essence, design will always exist in relation to the user (unless it's an avant garde project designed to subvert the user-centric philosophy), and the primary market for branded goods with huge logos is the nouveau riche (often synonymous with tasteless). whether bigger logo = tackier is irrelevant, but the consensus is that consumer of a certain social class/attitude seek conspicuous consumption and huge logos do just the job stands, thus the companies will take on that observation and cater accordingly.

@thatwasntverypradaofyou @_arsenick_ god it’s painful watching two people bicker over which luxury brand has a bigger logo and thus tackier. Just read books on the business aspects of luxury brand, they’re all the same. There’s an inverse relationship between logo size and the price of the item, so if you keep seeing tacky Gucci/Chanel/Lux branded anything with huge logos, it’s because you keep seeing a bunch of unbearable nouveau riche who buy the lower end of collection just to look rich. Lux brands need to sell cheaper items to the masses to fund their more exclusive creations like haute coutures, and they do that by making the logos big so people can feel good about their social status.
